inking about using AssertJ according to the user's request. I need to check if the public top-level test class requirement is met. The existing BsonTest might be a non-public class, which contradicts this requirement. Should I adjust it? Maybe I could make BsonTest public, but it's currently just a placeholder. Since all top-level tests must adhere to this guideline, it might be best to make it public or package-private to resolve any violations. Creating a new CreatorExecutableTest could improve the situation too!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Deciding on test structure**\\n\\nI need to decide on the tests for the CreatorExecutableTest class. I'm considering whether to add four individual @Test methods or just one that covers everything. The class name should reflect its dedicated purpose, and it would be ideal to achieve a one-to-one mapping for coverage.\\n\\nFor implementation, I’m looking at how to structure the codec appropriately. Should I include a public no-arg constructor and setters for automatic decoding? The NoArgumentFactoryPojo might need a static factory method with appropriate access control. I also need to ensure instance creators set properties correctly.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering class construction**\\n\\nI need to decide if the class should have a private no-argument constructor. If it does, that might be okay since factory methods can still call private constructors. This could be beneficial to control how instances are created. However, I want to ensure that this design choice aligns with the overall structure and functionality of the class. It feels like a small detail, but it might have important implications for how instances of the class are handled later on.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_JnNstHLmlxCsQId82GtzCBhu|fc_0a180273461c0d640169f14450286c819183fe185059a4e6b2", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "javap -classpath ~/.gradle/caches/modules-2/files-2.1/org.mongodb/bson/4.11.1/b